Twenty years ago, Hurricane Katrina devastated New Orleans and the Gulf Coast, taking more than 1,800 lives and displacing thousands of families.

This tragedy exposed the painful truth about racial inequities, poverty, and the government’s failure to respond when underserved communities were most in need. 

The storm was a wake-up call that climate change has diminished crucial natural buffers against hurricanes throughout the Gulf - severely impacting ecosystems and communities.

As we mark this anniversary, we honor the resilience of survivors, the lives lost, and the communities that fought to rebuild against all odds. And we recommit ourselves to ensuring that never again will vulnerable communities be left behind in the face of disaster.

#HurricaneKatrina

Like countless other daughters of the diaspora, Marcus Garvey has inspired me since my earliest days. It’s past time that all Americans learn the truth of his legacy, so they might celebrate him as the changemaker, trailblazer, and hero we know he was.

That is why I introduced my new legislative initiative, the Marcus Garvey Legacy Package, which would exonerate him of the false, unjust, racially motivated charges that have stained his name for a century, as well as establish Marcus Garvey Recognition Day to commemorate his life and achievements.

The Legacy Package is the key to cementing Marcus Garvey’s rightful place in history and honoring his undeniable contributions to Black history and the cause of freedom, and I am filled with pride at the opportunity to champion this effort in Congress.

Today, I join my fellow New Yorkers in expressing my deep condolences to the family and loved ones of New York Police Department Officer Didarul Islam, as well as to each of our Bangladeshi neighbors who are mourning the loss of a true community hero. Officer Islam’s story was not unlike that of many New Yorkers across our city. He migrated to this nation in search of opportunity and possibility, found work serving his city, and raised a family he cherished with all his heart. He was a good man who exemplified everything an officer of the NYPD should aspire to be, and his passing in the line of duty during Monday’s senseless mass shooting is a tragedy in every sense of the word. My heartfelt sympathy and prayers go out to his expecting wife, their two young children, and the entire Bangladeshi-American Community in this time of terrible grief.

As Uterine Fibroid Awareness Month comes to a close, the work is far from over. Uterine fibroids affect millions of women—often in silence—across all backgrounds, yet the issue remains underrecognized and underfunded.
Earlier this month, I was honored to help bring visibility to this critical uterine health issue, including sharing a powerful message from Academy Award winning actor, @Lupita_Nyongo. These conversations matter and help to drive real change across the finish line.

Rest in peace to Malcolm-Jamal Warner, a true star in his own right.

He lit up our screens weekly as Theo Huxtable, a shining light at a time where positive, realistic depictions of young Black men and the Black family were far and few in between.  Everybody's older brother, Warner was a role model to so many, and his impact will remain.

The world has lost an immense talent, and my condolences are with his loved ones during this devastating time.

Congressman William Lacy "Bill" Clay Sr. was a trailblazing leader whose dedication to Missouri’s 1st Congressional District and to the mission of the Congressional Black Caucus left an enduring mark on our nation. As the first Black Congressman from Missouri, he opened doors and forged a path that generations of leaders have since followed. His legacy lives on in the progress he made and the lives he touched, and he will be deeply missed. My thoughts are with his family and loved ones during this difficult time.

@RepShontelBrown, @RepBonnie, and @Sen_Alsobrooks to reintroduce a myriad of legislation to support research and preventative measures to end uterine cancer and fibroids.

Our conversation was filled with tears and a myriad of emotion from women who are dealing with this disease, and I am eternally grateful that she took this moment to share her story and lend her powerful voice to the voiceless.

For 26 years, Hondurans and Nicaraguans on Temporary Protected Status have contributed to our communities and our country. When their nations abandoned them, America gave them a home. And I am so grateful it did, because I speak from experience when I say they have only made Brooklyn a better, more beautiful mosaic of cultures and peoples. 
 
Now, after decades as our neighbors and like so many other TPS holders, Donald Trump wants to see them expelled to unstable, unsafe, chaotic environments – all to fuel his hysterical obsession with mass deportation.
 
This xenophobic cruelty is not making America safer. It’s not making America stronger. It’s only ruining lives and hurting our communities, just so the president can hit the insane and inhumane deportation numbers he promised his base. Disgusting and despicable.
